Special Agent Richard Gill

From MAILER-DAEMON Sun Oct 22 15:30:45 1995
From: richard.gill@fbi.gov
To: cybercrime.taskforce@fbi.gov
Subject: I'm Not Dead
Date: Sun, 22 Oct 1995 15:30:45 -0400
Message-ID: <19951022153045.UVWX1234@fbi.gov>

Team,

Contrary to what our HR system might say, I am not dead. Someone (likely our hacker friends) has played a practical joke on us.

Keep focusing on the Ellingson case. Don't let this distraction derail our investigation.

And if anyone has any "condolences" for my family, you can keep them to yourself.

Very Much Alive,
Special Agent Richard Gill

From MAILER-DAEMON Sun Oct 22 20:45:10 1995
From: richard.gill@fbi.gov
To: deputy.director@fbi.gov
Subject: Ellingson Case - Unexpected Development
Date: Sun, 22 Oct 1995 20:45:10 -0400
Message-ID: <19951022204510.YZAB5678@fbi.gov>

Sir,

You're not going to believe this, but Ellingson has reached out to the young hackers for help. They're claiming these kids might be the key to stopping Belford.

I think this is a mistake. These are criminals, not consultants.

Request permission to intervene and bring these hackers into custody.

Special Agent Richard Gill

From MAILER-DAEMON Mon Oct 23 09:30:22 1995
From: richard.gill@fbi.gov
To: cybercrime.taskforce@fbi.gov
Subject: New Approach to Ellingson Case
Date: Mon, 23 Oct 1995 09:30:22 -0400
Message-ID: <19951023093022.CDEF9012@fbi.gov>

Team,

Against my better judgment, we've been ordered to work with Ellingson and these young hackers to catch Belford.

I want round-the-clock surveillance on these kids. If they so much as jaywalk, I want to know about it.

Remember, they're not our friends. They're assets at best, suspects at worst.

Stay sharp.

Special Agent Richard Gill

From MAILER-DAEMON Mon Oct 23 14:15:45 1995
From: richard.gill@fbi.gov
To: deputy.director@fbi.gov
Subject: Request for Transfer
Date: Mon, 23 Oct 1995 14:15:45 -0400
Message-ID: <19951023141545.GHIJ3456@fbi.gov>

Sir,

I've given this a lot of thought, and I believe it's time for me to move on from the Cybercrime Division.

This Ellingson case has shown me that I'm out of my depth with these tech-savvy criminals. Getting declared dead by a bunch of teenagers was the last straw.

I'd like to request a transfer back to Baltimore PD. I've spoken with some old colleagues, and they have an opening in their Homicide unit.

It's time I got back to some real police work, none of this cyber bunk.

Thank you for your understanding.

Special Agent Richard Gill

From MAILER-DAEMON Mon Oct 23 17:30:10 1995
From: richard.gill@fbi.gov
To: cybercrime.taskforce@fbi.gov
Subject: Farewell and Good Luck
Date: Mon, 23 Oct 1995 17:30:10 -0400
Message-ID: <19951023173010.KLMN7890@fbi.gov>

Team,

I wanted to let you all know that I've decided to leave the Cybercrime Division. I'll be returning to Baltimore to join their Homicide unit.

You're a talented group, and I know you'll crack this Ellingson case. As for me, I'm done with all this hacker bunk. Give me a good old-fashioned murder any day.

It's been an honor serving with you all. If you're ever in Baltimore, look me up. First round's on me.

Special Agent Richard Gill
Soon to be Detective Richard Gill, Baltimore PD

P.S. Whoever declared me dead in the system - well played. But remember, what goes around, comes around.
